recalls.Summary: Subaru of America, Inc. (Subaru) is recalling certain 2022 BRZ and Toyota GR86 vehicles.  The rear turn signals may intermittently become inoperative.
recalls.Consequence: Inoperative rear turn signals may not notify other drivers of a turning vehicle, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Dealers will replace both rear combination lamp assemblies, free of charge.  Owner notification letters were mailed January 8, 2024.  Subaru owners may contact Subaru's customer service at 1-844-373-6614.  Toyota owners may contact Toyota customer service at 1-800-331-4331.  Subaru's number for this recall is WRM-23.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.nhtsa.gov.

complaints.summary: Stock blinkers rapidly flash faster than normal, blinkers cannot be seen in the rear at the time when signaling left or right during this time

I purchased a new 2022 Subaru BRZ.  Shortly after the purchase, the wheel bolts loosened which caused catastrophic damage to the wheel, and all brake components.    Upon further research, we believe this may be an inherent vehicle defect.  This problem is subject to a recall involving hub bolts which can loosen to the point where the wheel can detach from the vehicle damaging the brake components and posses serious safety issue.   The consumer is requesting to reimbursed for repairs, rental, and legal fees.

This is a new car. There’s was only 31 miles when I purchased. One day, there’s some sound when I driving the vehicle. Once I parked,  all the warning lamps was on, then my car wasn’t able to move. When the incident happened, it was only 4 months of using it and only 5,498 miles. Then I bring my car back to retailer and they inform me I need to replace the whole engine because of lack of oil. Even though they Silas’s my car was lack of oil, but there’s no light on the dashboard lights up and told me I need to add more oil. The process of repairing took 5 months. After I read other owners post on social media, I believe I have the similar situation. It says “ RTV is a sealant used as a gasket for the Subaru FA24D engine in the car and is allegedly applied too liberally at the factory. When RTV is dislodged in the engine's oil, it can clog the pickup. That can cause oil starvation“   Roughly a month later of fixing it(5 months of repairs) , there’s a strong scent of gas when I open the door of my car. And I can’t turn it on the first time. Second time of trying turning it on, all the warning lamp went off again. And the car couldn’t drive again. I bring back to the retailer and this is their respond, “ the technician found fuel is pouring out of the pressure relief valve of the left side head due to a possible failing injector on cylinder #3. We must do a teardown to verify the initial diagnosis.” And the final diagnosis The technician found two injector o-rings that were defective, causing fuel to leak and flood the cylinder chamber, which in turn caused the vehicle to stall. Parts can fail for many reasons, in this case we can attribute it to the quality of the parts themselves.“

During my early commute on a sunny morning shortly after sunrise with the sun at the rear of the vehicle, when selecting the turn signal, the dash display flashes rapidly, i.e., hyperflashing, and it has been confirmed that the rear signal light does not operate during this anomaly.  The forward turn signal does function but flashes at a rapid rate.  This is a repeatable occurrence when the sun is behind the car in the early morning from early sunrise to about 60 minutes later.  Once the sun is high in the sky, the turn signals operate normal.  This condition occurs on either turn signal and I have also experienced this with late afternoon sun.  I have captured this anomaly on video but this site does not allow upload of .mp4 files.  This is a link to a video I uploaded on YouTube showing the anomaly in later afternoon sun.    https://youtu.be/dHwMCdlJfYQ  I have communicated this concern to Subaru of America and shared the video links to them.  Their last communication was to contact a dealer.  I understand that the dealer would need to confirm my concern.  However, it would need to be a sunny day on the time of appointment plus the duty hours for the technicians are outside the window of the sun elevation when this problem occurs.    Other owners of the 2022 BRZ and Toyota GR86 have reported similar experiences on the web forums with turn signals behaving as I have detailed.

When the sun is facing the rear of the car, the rear turn signals do not activate, and the turn signals flash rapidly. It is exactly what happens in this youtube video:  https://youtu.be/dHwMCdlJfYQ  This is a danger, because my car will not properly signal when I change lanes or take a turn.  Subaru will not look at the vehicle. In this post in a community of owners for this vehicle, an owner states that the dealer ignored the issue, and Subaru of America sent a generic, irrelevant response.  https://www.gr86.org/threads/fast-blinker-caused-by-low-sun.4733/post-96056  This behavior by the dealer and the manufacturer is irresponsible and dangerous. This issue needs to be resolved at the federal level to ensure the safety of myself and others on the road.

Found traces of silicone in my engine. Checked the dipstick out of curiosity  and found silicone or RTV sealant. The car only has 500 miles on it. Will do oil change after break in period of Subaru’s recommended 1000 miles and will have them check the oil pan filter for more RTV…
The engine has excess RTV sealant and is clogging the oil pick-up tube. This is cause the motor to have restricted oil flow and causing premature motor failures.

The new 2022 Subaru BRZ's and Toyota GR86's have been found to have an excessive amount of RTV silicone on the engine oil pan. This can clog up the oil pickup filter and cause oil starvation leading to catastrophic engine failure. A few engines have already failed and more people have been finding RTV silicone in their oil filters and dipsticks including me.
My car has excess RTV sealant on the oil pan that has now gotten into my engine and is causing oil starvation.

These particular vehicles (and their Toyota counterpart, the GR86) have been experiencing issues with excess RTV sealant used on the oil pan and timing cover getting into the oil.  Once this RTV sealant is in the oil, it clogs the oil pickup tube filter.  As the excess sealant collects on the filter, it begins to starve the engine of oil.  There have been a number of documented failures so far (including one that made international auto news).    Some owners are inspecting their oil dip stick and finding anywhere from light to heavy sealant residue even on the dip stick.  I inspected my own and found traces of RTV sealant stuck to it as well.  In the provided picture, you will see traces of sealant on the length of the dip stick as well as the tip.  At this time, Toyota and Subaru have not issued a recall or service bulletin of any sort for this problem.  The online forums for these vehicles are filled with nothing but posts about finding sealant on their dipsticks, or posts from those that removed their own oil pan and found sealant clogging the filter.

issues.title: High-Pitched Noise from Engine Bay
issues.description: Many owners report a high-pitched whining or whistling noise coming from the engine bay, particularly during acceleration or at certain RPM ranges. The noise is often attributed to the direct injection fuel system or intake components.
symptoms: Sound most noticeable at certain RPMs
issues.fix_description: Often considered normal operation by dealers, but some cases resolved with intake system adjustments or software updates
issues.prevention: Regular maintenance and using recommended fuel octane rating

issues.title: Infotainment System Freezing and Glitches
issues.description: The 8-inch touchscreen infotainment system experiences freezing, slow response times, and occasional complete system crashes. CarPlay and Android Auto connectivity issues are also commonly reported.
issues.fix_description: Software updates from dealer, system reset, or in severe cases, head unit replacement
issues.prevention: Keep system software updated and avoid rapid temperature changes

issues.title: Cricket Chirping Noise from Transmission
issues.description: Owners report a cricket-like chirping sound coming from the manual transmission area, particularly when the clutch is engaged or during gear changes. The noise is often present from new vehicles.
issues.fix_description: Often considered normal by Subaru, some cases improved with transmission fluid change or clutch adjustment
issues.prevention: Proper clutch operation and regular transmission maintenance

issues.title: Rear Tire Wear Issues
issues.description: Premature and uneven rear tire wear, particularly on the inside edges. This appears to be related to the rear suspension geometry and alignment specifications from the factory.
symptoms: Inside edge wear on rear tires
issues.fix_description: Professional alignment, possible suspension component adjustment, tire rotation
issues.prevention: Regular tire rotations, proper alignment checks, avoid aggressive driving

issues.title: Clutch Pedal Feel and Engagement Issues
issues.description: Some owners report inconsistent clutch pedal feel, difficulty finding the engagement point, or clutch judder during engagement. Issues may be related to clutch hydraulics or clutch disc quality.
issues.fix_description: Clutch hydraulic system bleeding, clutch adjustment, or in severe cases clutch replacement
issues.prevention: Proper clutch operation technique, regular brake fluid changes

issues.title: Paint Quality and Chipping Issues
issues.description: Reports of thin paint that chips easily, particularly on the front bumper, hood, and around wheel wells. Some colors appear more susceptible than others.
symptoms: Rock chips on hood and bumper
issues.fix_description: Touch-up paint, paint protection film installation, or professional paint repair
issues.prevention: Apply paint protection film, avoid following vehicles closely, regular washing

issues.title: Door Handle and Trim Rattles
issues.description: Interior rattles from door handles, dashboard trim pieces, and other interior components. Most commonly reported during cold weather or on rough road surfaces.
issues.fix_description: Trim panel removal and proper securing, adding foam padding, or trim piece replacement
issues.prevention: Regular interior cleaning, avoiding extreme temperature changes

issues.title: Fuel System Evaporative Emissions Issues
issues.description: TSB issued for potential fuel vapor leak in the evaporative emission system, which can trigger check engine lights and emissions test failures.
issues.fix_description: Inspection and replacement of EVAP system components per TSB procedures
issues.prevention: Ensure proper fuel cap sealing, avoid overfilling fuel tank

issues.title: Automatic Transmission Rough Shifting
issues.description: Owners with automatic transmissions report harsh or delayed shifts, particularly during cold weather operation or low-speed maneuvering.
issues.fix_description: Transmission software update, fluid change, or in severe cases transmission repair
issues.prevention: Regular transmission service, proper warm-up procedures

issues.title: Wind Noise Around Door Seals
issues.description: Excessive wind noise entering the cabin, particularly around door seals and window weatherstripping at highway speeds.
issues.fix_description: Door seal adjustment or replacement, weatherstripping service, window alignment check
issues.prevention: Regular door seal inspection and cleaning

editorial.tagline: Pure driving joy, refined and more powerful
editorial.hero_blurb: The second-generation BRZ emerges as a more mature sports car that doesn't compromise its core philosophy. With a larger 2.4-liter boxer engine and refined dynamics, it addresses the original's power concerns while maintaining its brilliant balance and affordability.
editorial.essence: The BRZ represents what happens when you perfect an already excellent formula. It's a proper driver's car that prioritizes feel over flash, delivering genuine sports car thrills without the complexity or cost of exotic machinery.
editorial.heritage: Born from the Toyota-Subaru partnership that created the original GT86/BRZ in 2012, the second-generation BRZ builds on nearly a decade of real-world feedback. This collaboration brought rear-wheel-drive sports cars back to the masses, reviving the affordable sports coupe segment.
editorial.design_philosophy: Subaru focused on the three pillars of lightweight construction, low center of gravity, and balanced handling. The design prioritizes driver engagement over straight-line speed, creating a car where you can explore its limits safely and enjoyably on public roads.
editorial.motorsport_history: While relatively new to motorsport, the BRZ platform has found success in grassroots racing, from autocross to track days. Its balanced chassis and modification-friendly nature have made it a favorite in amateur racing circles and time attack events.
editorial.engine_character: The 2.4-liter naturally aspirated boxer four delivers linear power with a distinct growl. It pulls cleanly from 3000 RPM and rewards rev-happy driving, though it lacks the explosive torque of turbocharged rivals. The engine feels eager and responsive, begging to be worked.
editorial.transmission_feel: The six-speed manual offers precise, mechanical shifts with well-defined gates. The clutch is progressive and communicative, making heel-toe downshifts a joy. Each gear change feels deliberate and satisfying, connecting driver to machine.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: Beautifully balanced with slight understeer that transitions to controlled oversteer when provoked. The chassis feels alive and communicative, telegraphing grip levels clearly. It's predictable at the limit yet playful enough to make every drive engaging.
editorial.steering_feel: Direct, unassisted hydraulic-like feel with excellent on-center precision. The steering loads up progressively in corners and provides clear feedback about front tire grip. Weight is perfectly calibrated - not too light, not too heavy.
editorial.brake_confidence: Strong, progressive brakes with excellent pedal feel and minimal fade during spirited driving. The system provides confidence-inspiring stopping power that matches the car's dynamic capabilities, though track use may require upgraded pads.
editorial.sound_signature: The boxer engine produces a distinctive rumble that's more refined than the original. Under acceleration, it develops a purposeful growl that builds intensity with RPM, while the exhaust note has a satisfying bark on downshifts.
editorial.ideal_owner: Driving purists who value engagement over outright speed, weekend canyon carvers, and enthusiasts seeking an affordable entry into proper sports car ownership. Perfect for those who appreciate mechanical precision and analog driving experiences.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Power-hungry drag racers, daily commuters needing practicality, or drivers seeking luxury appointments. Those wanting effortless highway passing or impressive straight-line acceleration numbers should look elsewhere.
editorial.buyers_summary: The second-generation BRZ finally addresses the power complaints while maintaining everything that made the original special. It's the sports car for drivers who understand that connection and engagement matter more than horsepower numbers.

expertReviews.title: 2014 vs. 2022 Subaru BRZ - POV Comparison
pros: 2022 BRZ has significantly more power and torque with no torque dip
First gen BRZ has much larger trunk opening for practicality
Both generations are very reliable and hold their value well
Excellent daily driver sports cars that are affordable and fun
Easy to work on and modify with similar mounting points
Great heel-toe downshifting and manual transmission experience
cons: First gen BRZ has major torque dip between 3000-5000 RPM
Second gen BRZ is less engaging with more isolation from road
Second gen has smaller trunk opening despite same trunk space
First gen lacks low-end torque making it feel sluggish below 4500 RPM
Second gen has more assisted steering with less feedback
expertReviews.verdict: The 2022 BRZ is objectively better with more power, better suspension tuning, and refined dynamics, but the 2014 BRZ offers a more raw, visceral driving experience with better road feedback. The first gen is more fun for daily spirited driving despite the torque dip, while the second gen is faster and more capable at the limit. Both are excellent value propositions - save $10k with a used first gen or get the improved second gen for around $30k.

expertReviews.title: TURBO 2ND GEN BRZ / GR86 LONG TERM REVIEW
pros: Turbo kit transforms the car completely - feels like how it should have come from factory
Excellent reliability with 65,000 miles and turbo setup - only one code issue related to evap canister
Factory clutch still holding up after 30,000 miles with 100hp boost (220hp to 325hp)
Outstanding aftermarket support with multiple body kit options available immediately
Linear power delivery with JDL turbo kit - very smooth and factory-like appearance
Great handling car that's perfect for building and customization
Reversible turbo installation with oil pan swap for maintenance
cons: Multiple warning lights and codes appearing (check engine, traction control, etc.)
Evap canister issues when turbocharged due to missing rear fender liner
Expensive modification - total turbo setup costs around $10,000-11,000
Conservative tune at only 8 PSI - not maximizing potential power
Requires additional modifications like injectors and fuel pump
expertReviews.verdict: After 65,000 miles with a JDL turbo kit, this 2022 BRZ has proven to be remarkably reliable and transformed into what the reviewer considers the car should have been from factory. Making 325 wheel horsepower on a conservative tune, the turbo setup has been trouble-free except for an evap canister issue. The reviewer highly recommends the BRZ/GR86 platform for anyone wanting to build rather than buy, praising its exceptional aftermarket support and customization potential. Plans to add flex fuel and retune for 450hp show there's still more potential to unlock.

expertReviews.title: 2022 Subaru BRZ Review: Sensational Driver's Car! Even ...
pros: Significantly improved 2.4L engine with better torque curve and 23-27 more horsepower
50% stiffer chassis allows for better suspension tuning
Still lightweight under 3000 pounds with naturally aspirated engine
Functional aerodynamic elements and aluminum panels reduce weight
Good value at $30,555 for a proper sports car
Deep bolstered cloth seats ideal for track use
Rear-wheel drive with limited slip differential
cons: Automatic transmission adds $1600, 49 pounds, and reduces engagement
Extremely small rear seats and limited trunk space
17-inch wheels on Premium trim have less grippy Michelin Primacy tires
Nine years between generations with minimal first-gen updates
expertReviews.verdict: The second-generation BRZ successfully improves on the original formula without losing its essence. The new 2.4L engine delivers much better torque delivery (peak at 3700rpm vs 6400rpm) and more power, while the 50% stiffer chassis enables better handling. It remains a lightweight, naturally aspirated, rear-wheel drive sports car that stays true to its pure driving mission. However, the automatic transmission significantly compromises the experience.

expertReviews.title: What We Learned After Testing a Subaru BRZ for 40000 Miles
pros: Excellent driving dynamics and handling balance
Great fuel economy - averaged 26 MPG vs EPA 22 MPG
Lightweight rear-drive performance car with engaging experience
Good value - gives 80% of Porsche driving experience for third the price
Works well in winter with proper snow tires
Engine, shifter, pedals work in harmony
cons: Very noisy cabin - 91 dB with fake engine sound system
Fake engine noise pumped through speakers with no easy disable
Limited steering wheel telescoping range for tall drivers
Difficult clutch feel - takes adjustment period
Stock brakes overheat quickly on track
Expensive dealership service charges
expertReviews.verdict: The BRZ nails the formula for lightweight, affordable rear-drive performance. Despite minor complaints about noise and ergonomics over 40,000 miles, it delivers exceptional driving engagement and fun factor. Works surprisingly well in winter and responds well to track modifications. Makes BRZ and GR86 worthy of 10 Best award.

expertReviews.title: it only took 2 Generations to make this car perfect.. | Subaru ...
pros: Extremely comfortable for long road trips
Reliable and fuel efficient at 30 mpg
Fun to drive with engaging driving experience
Ice cold AC performs well in extreme heat
Versatile with potential for different build directions
cons: Inferiority complex when surrounded by larger trucks
Needs loud exhaust to be noticed
Previous owner went through too many cars suggesting potential restlessness
expertReviews.verdict: The reviewer is extremely satisfied with the 2nd generation BRZ, calling it 'perfect' and 'dialed.' He emphasizes its comfort for daily driving and road trips, reliability, and fun factor. Despite considering other options like a WRX, he's decided to keep the BRZ long-term, appreciating its balance of sportiness and practicality. The car serves as his primary transportation while delivering consistent enjoyment.

expertReviews.title: New Subaru BRZ Review - Same Recipe but Better Executed!
pros: More power with 2.4L engine (230hp vs 200hp)
Better interior quality with improved materials and larger infotainment screen
Excellent handling with limited slip differential
Perfect balance between grip and controllable sliding
Comfortable Alcantara seats that hold you well
Quick steering ratio for precise adjustments
Maintains manual transmission and rear-wheel drive character
cons: Engine doesn't sound particularly great
Rev hangy at low speeds with poor throttle response in town
Steering less communicative than first generation
Very loud exhaust (on test car)
Back seats completely useless
Less of a sideways machine than first generation due to wider tires
expertReviews.verdict: The second generation BRZ is 'same same but better' - it retains all the great characteristics of the original while addressing the main complaint of lack of power. With 30 more horsepower and 50 more Nm of torque from the 2.4L engine, plus improved interior quality and better exterior styling, it's a significant improvement. The car maintains its fun, controllable character with the LSD working perfectly in both dry and wet conditions. Highly recommended with manual gearbox and traction control off for maximum enjoyment.
